'''Sir Joseph Burn''' [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]], [[Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors|FRICS]] (1871–1950) was chairman of the [[Prudential plc|Prudential Insurance]] company.<ref name=tate>{{cite web|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/burn-by-the-lake-t03214/text-catalogue-entry |title='By the Lake', Rodney J. Burn |publisher=Tate |date= |accessdate=2012-06-16}}</ref> He was a fellow of the [[Institute of Actuaries]] and served as the organization's president from 1926–1928. The "Sir Joseph Burn Prize" is awarded by the Institute of Actuaries to the UK student with the best performance in the actuarial exams, thereby becoming eligible to transfer to the Class of Fellow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actuaries.org.uk/students/pages/prizes-exam-performance |title=Prizes for exam performance &#124; The Actuarial Profession |publisher=Actuaries.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-06-16}}</ref>

== Personal background ==
Burn was married to Emily H. ([[née]] Smith) Burn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person.php?LinkID=mp97948 |title=National Portrait Gallery - Person - Emily H. Burn (née Smith) |publisher=Npg.org.uk |date=1929-06-26 |accessdate=2012-06-16}}</ref> They were the parents of Peggy Burn, Maurice Burn, and the painter, [[Rodney Joseph Burn]].<ref name=tate/>

